An attempt was made to examine the impact of degraded wetland health on livelihood conditions, considering four socio-ecological parameters. This investigation utilised a correlation matrix (Fig. 6
                        ) and findings from various publications (Table 4
                        ). Although an extensive literature explores the relationship between wetland conditions and livelihood status, the studies featured in Table 4 were selectively chosen for their direct relevance to this investigation's specific research objectives and analytical approach. These carefully curated publications provided focused insights into the intricate linkages between distinct wetland types, varying forms of livelihood impacts, and the underlying mechanisms driving these connections across diverse geographical contexts. Rather than an exhaustive compilation, Table 4 represents a strategic selection of influential works that effectively illustrate the nuanced relationships between wetland degradation, livelihood status, and the consequential socioeconomic implications for dependent communities (Table 4). The correlation matrix and the quantified rate of wetland degradation determined the extent of effect and the significance levels among the parameters (Fig. 6). A negative relationship was discovered between the average wetland degradation rate (−0.38) and SDGI (Seifollahi-Aghmiuni et al., 2019; Xu et al., 2022) and indicating that focused efforts in the direction of reaching SDGs can decrease resource loss, including wetland degradation. The EPI was also negatively correlated with the rate of wetland loss (Papadimitriou et al., 2020; Wendling et al., 2022;) (−0.34) at a statistically significant level of 0.01 (Fig. 6). This suggests that countries that have invested heavily in improving their environmental performance tend to experience lower rates of wetland loss. Furthermore, the income classification exhibited a negative influence on the wetland degradation rate (−0.42), indicating that economically advanced nations are better equipped to minimise wetland degradation. Previous studies (Langergraber and Dotro, 2019; Wang et al., 2021) support this finding. Lastly, a negative correlation between the HDI and the rate of wetland loss (−0.38) was detected at a significance level of 0.05 (Fig. 6), suggesting that countries with higher HDI tend to experience lower rates of wetland health degradation. Therefore, enhancing HDI could be a comprehensive approach to protecting wetlands and mitigating their loss (Aydin-Kandemir and Demir, 2022).
